  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identity\n- Understanding the nature of customer business\n- Assessing money laundering risks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Submitting suspicious transaction reports\n- Filing currency transaction reports\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Keeping records for specified periods\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Implementing risk-based compliance programs\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring of transactions\n- Identifying high-risk customers or transactions\n\n5. Employee Training\n- Providing anti-money laundering (AML) training\n- Ensuring staff understand compliance procedures\n- Teaching how to recognize suspicious activities\n\n6. Compliance with Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) requirements\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n- Implementing internal control systems\n\n7. Screening\n- Checking customers against sanctions lists\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring politically exposed persons (PEPs)\n\nThese obligations vary by jurisdiction but generally aim to prevent financial crimes.",
